{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_foster_ver01/data/sn92066980/00517010190/1911021801/0455.xml":{"full_text":"SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 1\u00ab, Wil.\nSUE ROADS\nIN COURTS\nUNION PACIFIC COAL COMPANY\nAND UNION PACIFIC RAIL\nROAD COMPANY MADE\nDEFENDANTS TODAY\nActions Begun in United States Court\nat Cheyenne to Cancel Patents to\nLarge Tracts of Coal Land Which\nAre Alleged to Have Been Obtain\ned by Fraud and With Dummy En\ntrymen \u2014Areas Cancelled.\nO Cheyenne, Wyo., Feb. 15.\u2014The O\nQ Union Pacific Coal company and O\nO the Union Pacific Railroad com- O\nO pany were today made defendants O\nO in a suit brought in th 9 United G\nO States court here by the govern- C\nO ment to cancel patents so lirge Q\nO tracts of coal land which, It is O\nO alleged, were obtained by fraud O\nO and with dummy entrymen. O\n00000000000000000\nHELD FOR CANCELLATION.\nThirty-two Coal Land Entries in the\nLander Land District.\nWashington, Feb. 15. \u2014Decisions\nhanded down by the commissioner of\nthe general land office held for can\ncellation thirty-two entries, embracing\nvaluable coal lands in the Lander, Wy\noming, land district, upon the ground\nthat tne entries were made fraudu\nlently in pursuance of conspiracy and\nby means of dummy entrymen.\nTransferred to Companies.\nThe lands were transferred to the\nNorthwestern Coal company and the\nOwl Creek Coal company, alleged to\nhave been -organized for the purpose\nof taking them over.\nMillion Dollars Involved.\nAbout ninety-five hundred acres of\ncoal land, valued at a million dollars,\nare involved.\nO Daughter of Famous Scout. O\nO Lander, Wyo., Feb. 15. \u2014Napo- O\nO leon B. Kinnear, a wealthy ranch- O\nO man of the Shoshone reservation, O\nO was shot and killed last night by O\nO bls brother-in-law, Joseph Baker, O\nO a half-breed Shoshone. O\nO Mrs. Kinnear was the daughter O\nO of Jim Baker, the famous scout O\nO and companion of Kit Carson. O\nO Indian police from Wind River O\nO agency are hunting for Baker. O\n00000000000000000\nWANTS HATCHERY.\nNew Albany Petition Asking That It\nBe Located Near that Place.\nBy Albert Richards.\nSpecial to The Republic**.\nNew Albany, Wyo., Feb. 15. \u2014A peti\ntion is being circulated here to have\nthe fish hatchery located at New Al\nbany, on the south fork of the Little\nLaramie. There is a good spring near\nthe right of way of the Laramie Plains\nline. No definite proposition has been\nmade yet, but the community will un\ndoubtedly give the site and may be\nhelp with the reconstruction of the\nbuildings.\nLIKE OLD FRIENDS.\nThe Longer You Know Them the Bet\nter You Like Them.\nDoan's Kidney Pills never fail you.\nLaramie people know this.\nRead this Laramie case.\nRead how Doan\u2019s stood the test.\nFor four years.\nIt's local testimony and can be in\nvestigated:\nHoward Coolican, 709 south Third\nstreet, Laramie, Wyo., says: \u201cIn Au\ngust, 1906/1 gave a statement for pub\nlication regarding the great benefit I\nhave obtained through the use of\nDoan\u2019s Kidney Pills and now, after a\nlapse of three years I am glad to con\nfirm all I then said. My back ached\nand I had sharp pains through my\nkidneys. There was a dull ache across\nmy loins which also caused me great\nmisery. I believe that the trouble was\nbrought on by the jarring and jolting\nof the engine. Procuring Doan\u2019s Kid\nney puis from the Laramie Drug Co.,\nI began their use and they proved so\nbeneficial that I do not hesitate to rec\nommend them. I have taken this rem\nedy on occasions since then and have\nnever been disappointed in the re\n\u2022ults.\"\n*\"or sale by all dealers. Pries 50\ncents. FoatarMilbum On, Buffalo,\nNew York, sale agents for ths United\nStates..\nRenMmtor\nTRAVELING CONVENTION\nAT BAPTIST CHURCH.\nThere will be what is called a trav\neling convention at the Baptist church\nnext Sunday morning and evening and\non Monday night. As the distances are\nso great in our state for the people to\ngo to the different conventions, and 1\non this account very few are able to 1\ngo, so It has been decided to bring\nthe convention to the people. On Sun\nday morning Miss Carrie O. Mills\npaugh will speak at the close of the\nSunday school hour, and at 11 o\u2019clock\nRev. C. A. Cook, D. D., of Spokane,\nWash., will deliver an address on\n\u2018\u2018Home Misssion.\u201d Miss Mlllspaugh\nwill address the young people at 6:30.\nRev. F. J. Bradshaw will speak at\n7:30. Rev. Bradshaw has spent seven\nteen years in China, he is just home\nfrom the field. His message will inter\nest you. On Monday night at 7:30,\nRev. A. L. Wadsworth pf; the Pacific\ncoast will speak. These are all repre\nsentative men of the Baptist denom\nination and are worth going to hear.\nThe public is cordially invited to all\nthe services.\nTHE RAILROAD\nIS SUEDTODAY\nWALTER ROGERS WANTS ELEV.\nEN THOUSAND DOLLARS FOR\nFALSE IMPRISONMENT.\nDeclined to Pay Pullman Fare on a\nTrain Made Up Exclusively of\nPullman Passenger Cars and Plac\ned in Hands of Officers Upon Ar\nrival of Train in Laramie.\nWalter A. Rogers, by his attorneys,\nGroesbeck Eby, today began suit\nfor damages against the Union Pa\ncific Railroad company, asking $11,350\ndamages for false arrest and impris\nonment, the petition being filed in the\noffice of the clerk of the district court.\nIt is more than likely that when the\ncase is called in the district court a\nmotion will be made to transfer the\ncase to the United States court at\nCheyenne, that being the usual course\nin such cases.\nArrested in Laramie.\nRogers, with two companions, board\ned a train at Sidney, Neb., with tick\nets to Laramie. They boarded a day\ncoach at Sidney, in which they rode\nto Cheyenne. There the train was\nmade up anew and the day coach was\nleft off, the train consisting of accom\nmodation only for passengers in Pull\nman cars. The three men declined to\npay the extra fare demanded for rid\ning in Pullman cars, and at Sherman\nConductor Frank Bevans, in charge of\nthe train wired ahead to have tb^\nthree men arrested. They were ar\nrested and placed In the county jail,\nlater being released on bail.\nThe three men were charged with\ntrespass, and later Rogers was given\na hearing before Justice Hynds, being\ndischarged. The cases against the\nother two were not tried and there\nthe matter rested until today, when\nthe petition for damages was filed. The\nfacts are all set forth at considerable\nlength In the petition.\nCourt House Notes.\nUnder Sheriff Stirling had not re\nturned from the country this after\nnoon.\nCharles B. Boyce, assessor of Car\nbon county, was at the court house\nthis afternoon, in consultation with\nDeputy Assessor Guy Dayton.\nJ. W. Brenning today filed proof of\nlabor on the Lucky Strike and Cop\nper Queen mining claims.\nJohn H. Symons sold to Helen Sy\nmons, for $1 and other valuable con\nsiderations, the east half of lots 1 and\n2, block 3, Union Pacific fourth addi\ntion to Laramic.\nPRINTED SIGNS IN\nTHE FOREST RESERVE.\nSupervisor Lovejoy will have print\ned signs erected at intervals in the\nMedicine Bow forest reserve, showing\nnot only the roads and their destina\ntion, but their physical condition. Thp\nsigns will contain a legend that will\ngive a clew to the physical condition\nof the road, whether good, passable, in\nbad shape or otherwise, one road, the\nsupervisor says, bearing the legend,\n\u201cCrosses the creek twenty times and\nall bridges out.\u201d Heretofore these\nnotices were of paper and cloth, which\nsquirrels and other animals tore down\nfor nesting purposes, and they were\nsoon abllterated. The signs will be\nposted at all roads leaving the main\ntrails.\nCHUGWATER MAN\n\u2022ENT TO PRISON.\nThomas Wheaton, who entered ths\nhouse of a rerident of Chugwater and\ntook several articles of clothing, was\nfound guilty in the district court at\nCheyenne and sentenced to a term of\ntwelve months and not more than\nthirteen moeths tn the state prison at\nRawlins.\nTHE LARAMIE REPUBLICAN\u2014 WEEKLY EDITION.\nHEADING FOR\nGREATWEST\nHIGHER OFFICIALS OF UNION PA\nCIFIC EXPECTED TO MAKE\nINSPECTION TRIP.\nAt Ogden They Will Order Double\nTracking of Line East of That\nCity Through Weber Canon\nFreight Congestion of Few Years\nAgo Due to Inadequate Trackage.\nPresident Lovett, Vice President\nivruiibcnnjti and otner high omc\u00bbuL\nui tne Harriman lines are expected iu\nogaen tue coming week to aeciue on\nme improvements mobt urgen.ly de\nmanded by the Union Pacific and\nouutnem Paciuc in and around Ogden,\nand, It is confidently asserted, that, as\na result of the visit, the first of the\ndouble trackage of the Union Pacific\nwill be from Ogden east through Web\ner canon.\nNeed of Second Line.\nJames J. Hill, at the time of the\nfrelgln congestion in 1906-7, confessed\nthat the railroads of the United States\nwere years behind the traffic require\nments. If that were true then, what\nwill be the degree of Inefficiency of the\nrailroads when, in the natural course\nof events, the country, regaining its\nequilibrium, begins to tax mine and\nfactory and farm to capacity to meet\nthe wants of a nation of over 92,000,-\n000 people?\nA Wise Decision.\nThe Harriman executive committee\nis acting wisely in beginning this early,\nyet opportunely, to escape the culpa\nbility that must attach to other rail\nroad managers when through failure\nto improve their lines in a period of\ncomparative inactivity they shall find\nwith a return of prosperity their trans\nportation facilities to be wholly in\nadequate? That reasoning has led\nlocal railroad men to affirm that not\nonly will the Union Pacific and South\nern Pacific be double-tracked before\nthe opening of the world\u2019s fair, but\nthe work of improving will begin im\nmediately and be rushed to completion\nas soon as possible.\nWill Be Made Manager Here.\nAs intimated in The Republican a\nfew days ago, C. L. Carlson of Chey\nenne, at present an operator in the of\nfice at that place, will be made mana\nger of the Laramie office of the West\nern Union, taking the place made va\ncant by the resignation of Did Smith,\nand which has been held temporarily\nby Mr. Bridgeman. The latter will re\nturn to the office here as an operator,\nrelieving Mr. Somerville, who will\ntake the night shift at the train order\ninstruments. Mr. Carlson will be here\nnext week.\nThe January Payroll.\nThe January payroll for the em\nployes of the Laramie Plains line is\nbeing prepared by Auditor Woods asd\nthe checks will be sent out later in the\nweek.\neoooooooooooooooo\nQ GOULD WILL RETIRE. O\n0 o\nO President of Missouri Pacific O\nO Will Become Chairman. O\nO O\nO New York, Feb. 15. \u2014George J. O\nO Gould, president of the Missouri C\nO Pacific, this afternoon issued a O\nO statement regarding the report O\nO of a contest for control of the O\nO Missouri Pacific, stating that he O\nO would retire from the presidency O\nO of the road and become O\nO chairman of the board of direc- O\nO tors. O\nOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOG\nIS HERE TO STUDY\nASSESSMENT METHODS\nCharles B. Boyce of Baggs, Wyo.,\nwho was recently elected assessor of\nCarbon county, is here Wednesday, con\nferring with Deputy Assessor Guy\nDayton as to the methods to be pur\nsued in this county. Mr. Boyce was for\nmerly editor and publisher of the\nSnake River Sentinel at Baggs, and\nIs the personal friend of Dr. E. G.\nCondit, formerly of Laramie, the broth\ner of Assistant Postmaster Condit of\nthis city.\nNEW BASE MAP OF\nMEDICINE BOW FOREST.\nDraftsmen in the forest office here\nare just completing a new base map\nof the Medicine Bow forest, showing\nevery physical feature of that reserve\nup to date, including some of the out\nlying tracts contiguous to the forest.\nThs map will show the streams, the\ntelephone lines, the roads, the rail\nroads, the trains, the camps, the cab-1\nins, the stopping places and the look-\nouts, making a very handy map for,\nanyone who wishes to traverse the re\naervee. The supervisor, Mr. Lovejoy,\nbopss to have enough of those printed\npersonal paragraphs.\nFrom Wednesday's Daily.\nH. B. Ellis of Denver is here.\nG. L. Wright is here from Fillmore.\nR. O. George Is here from Tie Sid\ning.\nL. H. Bisbee arrived from Denver to\nday.\nC. H. Burns of Foxpark is in the\ncity.\nC. S. Price of Medicine Bow is in the\ncity.\nCharles B. Bryce of Rawlins Is in\nthe city.\nN. A. Tyler of Greeley, Colo., is in\nthe city.\nR. O. George left for Tie Siding thia\nmorning.\nPercy Clark left for Cheyenne this\nmorning.\nJ- W. Queary was here from Denver\nlast nlghL\nT. M. Wilson of Foxpark spent the\nnight here\nLe\u00dfoy Grant will return to Chey\nenne tonight.\nSam Cowley returned to Rock River\nthis afternoon.\nMrs. William Brandls left for Ogden\nthis afternoon.\nMrs. Joe Lane left for Rock River\nthis afternoon.\nPresident Merica is at Cheyenne to\nday on business.\nHugh Benfield returned home to\nRock River today.\nMrs. Harry Maynard left for Chey\nenne this morning.\nJohn McGill left this morning for\nCheyenne on business.\nS. L. Steen of St. Joseph is in iLara\nmie today on business.\nChris Larson left for Rawlins this\nafternoon on business.\nMrs. Reba M. Coen of Sherman\nspent the night in this city.\nMs. Will Goodale left for Cheyenne\nthis morning to visit friends.\nC. R. McGrew and O. H. Graves of\nOmaha spent the night in this city.\nAxel Olson of the tie plant left this\nafternoon for San Francisco on a visit.\nKnud Knudson was here from his\nLittle Laramie valley ranch last night.\nMrs. T. H. Tol iff and Mrs. Ralph\nHance left this morning for Wheat\nland.\nA. Hixson and W. J. Robinson of\nRock River spent teh night in this city\nWilliam J. Dalles and Oliver Harrold\nof Millbrook spent the night in this\ncity.\nW. H. Dearstyne of the Peters Paper\ncompany of Denver is in Laramie to\nday.\nCharles Stewart has returned to\nEncampment, after a few days visit\nhere.\nW. C. Schultz of Fremont, Neb., was\na business visitors to Laramie last\nnight.\nMrs. John Travelle and Miss Mag\ngie Blair left this morning for St.\nLouis.\nC. X. Thompson of Butte, Mont., was\na business visitor to Laramie last\nnight\nMisses Lu Seba Polmatier, Helene\nPolmatier, Ina K. Polmatier, E. Phyllis\nPolmatier and C. Pauline Polmatier\nwere registered at the Union Pacific\nlast night.\nJ. Peterson of Tie Siding was a busi\nness visitor to the county seat this\nmorning.\nR. L. Woodford of the Drew Cloth\ning company will leave tonight for the\neast to purchase goods.\nEight laborers for the Laramie,\nHahns Peak and Pacific railroad ar*\nrived from the east this afternoon.\nWilliam Robitaille and wife arrived\nthis afternoon from Cheyenne and are\nthe guests of Mr. and Mrs. Le\u00dfoy\nGrant, jr.\nD. M. Wilt and Owen 8. Cose of Fox\npark were here today, having some\nbusiness with Superintendent Stewart\nof the Laramie Plains line.\nWilliam Corbett of Omana. repre\nsenting the Baum Iron company of\nthat city, was here today, looking aft\ner the interests of that company in\nWyoming. He left on the morning\n*mln for Rawlins.\nA. Z. Ralphs of Cheyenne, who la\nestablishing a ten-cent store In the\nNaismith building, on Second street,\narrived from Cheyenne last nlghL His\nstock Is beginning to arrive and he la\nhe~e tc see to its installation.\nW. J. McClement, the special agest\nfor the Wyoming division was here\nthis morning. \u201cI never saw business\nso light in my line,\u201d ho said. \u201cSeems\nthat nobody has any desire to do any\nthing wrong these days around Lara\nmie.\u201d\nLOADING CONCENTRATES\nFROM RAMBLER MINE.\nYoung Mr. Crow, who came to the\ncity a few days ago from the Rambler\nmine, nys the Rambler company is\nloading a car of concentrates to be\n\u25a0hipped to the refinery In a few days.\nMen s Clothing Prices\nOur January Clean-up-Sale Is a hummer. We have made material\nreductions on many lines of our stock. How anxious we are to sell,\nthe deeply cut prices will bear sufficient evidence.\nMen\u2019s Suits worth up to AO\n$15.00 on sale at VV\nMen\u2019s Suits worth up to Fl IT\n$25.00 on sale at\nDon\u2019t wait until you see the big bargain your neighbor has\nbought, and it is too late for you to get one yourself.\nMEYER RAIFE\n310 Second Street. 310 Second Street.\nDEATH OF A PIONEER\nLADY OF CHEYENNE.\nOne of the most beloved and re\nspected pioneer women in the state,\nMrs. Ellen L. Bristol, wife of S. A.\nBristol, died early this morning at the\nfamily home, 208 East Twentieth\nstreet, says the Cheyenne Tribune.\nThe death was not wholly unexpected,\nas Mrs. Bristol had been suffering\nfrom cancer for a number of years,\nbut notwithstanding, brings as much\nregret and brief, as though peignant\nwith unexpectedness, into her home\nand the entire community. Mrs. Bris\ntol was one of the earliest members of\nthe Methodist church in this city, and\nher interest in its welfare never wav\nered up to the time of her death. There\nwas not a more tireless or enthusistlc\nworker in the church than she, even\nthough her age and health, were\nagainst her ambitions. Always ready\nto welcome a stranger and make them\nfeel at home, she did much to enlarge\nthe membership of her church. Ellen\nLee Bristol was born in 1839, in Guil\nford, Conn., and was aged 72 years. In\n1864 she married S. A. Bristol and\nmoved to Cheyenne in 1869, and has\nheld continuous residence here. The\ndeceased leaves a husband, S. A. Bris\ntol. three daughters, Mrs. Kate R.\nWade, Mrs. W. C. Mains, who live in\nCheyenne, and Mrs. Marshall M. At\nwell, who lives at Laramie, ana two\nsons, F. L. and Charles Bristol, both\nof whom live here. Mrs. N. E. Starn,\na sister, of Fort Morgan, Coio., will be\nhere to attend the funeral which will\nbe held from the Methodist church,\nFriday morning at 10 o\u2019clock.\nYou are probably aware that pneu\nmonia always results from a cold, but\nyou never heard of a cold resulting in\npneumonia when Chamberlain\u2019s Cough\nRemedy was used. Why take the risk\nwhen this remedy may be had for a\ntrifle? For sale by A. H. Cordlner'i\nDrug Store.\nHERE FOR A DAY\nAND HOME AGAIN.\nAugust Kassahn returned to Rock\nRiver today, after a stay of a day or\ntwo here,. James Mead also left for\nhis ranch home after a business visit\nto the county seat\nFAREWELL SUPPER TO\nDEPARTING FAMILY.\nThe Methodist church people of Bos\nler last night gave a farewell supper to\nMr. and Mrs. C. M. Anderson, who left\ntoday for Nebraska, where they will\nreside.\nMORE SNOW FALLS\nON BLACKBURN RANCH\nA. W. Augspurger returned from the\nBlackburn ranch yesterday afternoon,\nwhere he had been with Mr. Dumm of\nCasper and Rev. Dumm of this city on\na sight-seeing trip. Mr. Augspurger\nreports a fall of at least six Inches\nof snow on that ranch.\nA piece of flannel dampened with\nChamberlain's Liniment and bound on\nto the affected parts is superior to any\nplaster. When troubled with lame\nback or pains In the side or chest give\nit a trial and you are certain to be\nmore than pleased with the prompt re\nlief which it affords. Sold by Cordl\nner\u2019s Drug Store.\nWOOD HEATERS\nA big stock of all kinds o f CAST IRON and SHEET (ROM\nWOOD HEATERS at from\n$2.00 to $12.00\nLARAMIE FURNITURE COMPANY\nHAS NO CONNECTION\nWITH THE GOVERNMENT\nProf. A. D. Faville, animal husband\nman of the experiment station of the\nUniversity of Wyoming, says the sta\nion has no connection with the sheep\nowned by the government here and\nnear here, and that the death of the\ngovernment buck at the King ranch a\new days ago, mentioned in The Re\npublican Tuesday afternoon, did not in\nthe least affect the station.\nHOME FROM WEST\nON BUYING TRIP.\nMontle Blevins, the Walden stock\nman and ranchman, returned last\nnight from Rock Springs, where he\nhad been on business in connection\nwith his cattle trade, and will leave\nfor Walden on Saturday.\nSemi-Weekly Republican $2. a year.\nI write Life, Fire, Accident and\nHealth Insurance. Which do you need?\nE. A. McCLURE\nReal Estate, Insurance, Notary Public.\nConverse Building. Phono 107.\nZ. E. SEVISON\nCivil and Ini^fion Engineer\nSuite 15 Converse Building.\nW B. SCHILLING\nCivil Engineer\nSuit 5, Converse Building.\nA. W. FRENCH\nVETERINARIAN\nGraduate Kansas City Veterinary\nCollege, In government service 3 year*\nCall* Answered Day and Night.\nTelephone 58 red. Office Star Barn\nRes. Phone, 374 Pink.\nLARAMIE. WYO\nWHAT NEED YOU CARE\nabout the weather as long as you have\na bottle of our ginger ale to refresh\nyourself with! It is the one safest\ndrink to take in any weather. Just\nginger enough to be pleasant, just\nsweet enough to take the sharpness\noff. Suppose we send you a case. You\ncouldn\u2019t have a better beverage in\nyour house.\nN. C. PETERSON,\n410 Second St Phon, 131 y\n3","height":"20276","width":"14984"}}
